Overview¶

In Retail and E-Commerce (B2C) and in B2B, one of the key elements shaping the business strategy of a firm would be understanding of customer behaviour.¶

Such understanding would in turn help direct marketing to support this customer and improve the product offering efficiently.¶

In business, there are some golden rules that everyone needs to know:¶

"80% percent of our business comes from 20% of our customers."¶

"It costs 10 times less to sell to an existing customer than to find a new customer."¶

So, it’s important to understand who your top customers are that give consistent and increasing revenue streams for your business.¶

One of the simple and effective methodologies which are generally used in calculating customer value over a time frame is RFM¶

Business Understanding¶

Business Problem¶

An e-commerce company wants to segment its customers and determine marketing strategies towards these segments.¶

To achieve this objective,¶

we will define the purchase behavior of customers,¶

create different segments based on these behaviors, and¶

suggest some valuable marketing strategies for each segment.¶

Data Set Information:¶

This Online Retail II data set contains all the transactions occurring for a UK-based and registered, non-store online retail between 01/12/2009 and 09/12/2011.The company mainly sells unique all-occasion gift-ware. Many customers of the company are wholesalers.¶

Attribute Information:¶

InvoiceNo:¶

Invoice number. Nominal. A 6-digit integral number uniquely assigned to each transaction. If this code starts with the letter 'c', it indicates a cancellation.¶

StockCode:¶

Product (item) code. Nominal. A 5-digit integral number uniquely assigned to each distinct product.¶

Description:¶

Product (item) name. Nominal.¶

Quantity:¶

The quantities of each product (item) per transaction. Numeric.¶

InvoiceDate:¶

Invoice date and time. Numeric. The day and time when a transaction was generated.¶

UnitPrice:¶

Unit price. Numeric. Product price per unit in sterling (Â£).¶

CustomerID:¶

Customer number. Nominal. A 5-digit integral number uniquely assigned to each customer.¶

Country:¶

Country name. Nominal. The name of the country where a customer resides.¶

Clustering (Segmetation) Analysis based on RFM¶

What is RFM?¶

In [21]:
#Creating a new dataframe only for the RFM analysis
#First, grouping the dataframe based on Customer IDs, then Creating lastpurchase column, 
#then calculate the first factor of RFM (Recency)

rfm1 = df_filtered.groupby(by='Customer ID', as_index=False)['Date'].max()
rfm1.columns = ['Customer ID','Lastpurchase']
rfm1['Recency'] = rfm1['Lastpurchase'].apply(lambda x: (last_date - x).days)

In [25]:
#splitting RFM elements into 4 parts and Setting a score for each part depending on their weight/value.

df_rfm["RecencyScore"] = pd.qcut(df_rfm["Recency"], 4, labels = [4,3,2,1])
df_rfm["FrequencyScore"] = pd.qcut(df_rfm["Frequency"].rank(method = "first"), 4, labels = [1,2,3,4])
df_rfm["MonetaryScore"] = pd.qcut(df_rfm["Monetary"], 4, labels = [1,2,3,4])

In [37]:
#Adding another column Customized_seg to segment the customers in a very deep and customized way with different conditions and different RFM scores for each
df_rfm['Customized_seg'] = np.where((df_rfm['RecencyScore'] == 4) & (df_rfm['FrequencyScore'] == 4) & (df_rfm['MonetaryScore'] == 4) ,"Core Best Customers",
                            np.where((df_rfm['FrequencyScore'] == 4) & ((df_rfm['MonetaryScore'] == 1) | (df_rfm['MonetaryScore'] == 2)) ,"Promising Customers",
                                     np.where((df_rfm['RecencyScore'] == 4) & (df_rfm['FrequencyScore'] == 1) ,"Newest Customers",
                                               np.where( ( (df_rfm['RecencyScore'] == 1) & (df_rfm['FrequencyScore'] == 4) & (df_rfm['MonetaryScore'] == 4) ) ,"Lost Valued Customer (At Risk Customers)",
                                                         np.where( ( (df_rfm['RecencyScore'] == 1) & (df_rfm['FrequencyScore'] == 3) & (df_rfm['MonetaryScore'] == 3) ) ,"Lost Valued Customer (At Risk Customers)",
                                                        np.where(( ( (df_rfm['RecencyScore'] == 1) | (df_rfm['RecencyScore'] == 2) ) & (df_rfm['FrequencyScore'] == 4)),"Can't Lose Customers",
                                                                 np.where(( ( (df_rfm['RecencyScore'] == 1) | (df_rfm['RecencyScore'] == 2) ) & (df_rfm['FrequencyScore'] == 3)),"Can't Lose Customers",
                                                                 np.where((df_rfm['RecencyScore'] == 1) & (df_rfm['FrequencyScore'] == 1) & (df_rfm['MonetaryScore'] == 1), 'Lost Cheap Customers',
                                               "Not Segmented yet"))))))))

Suggested Marketing Strategies for different segments to direct marketing efforts efficently¶

Core Best Customers¶

RFM Score: 444

Who They Are:

Highly engaged customers who have bought the most recent, the most often, and generated the most revenue.

Marketing Strategies:

Focus on loyalty programs and new product introductions. These customers have proven to have a higher willingness to pay, so don't use discount pricing to generate incremental sales. Instead, focus on value added offers through product recommendations based on previous purchases.

For example:

Uber targets their "core" RFM customer segment, introducing their new Uber Eats offering.

Promising Customers¶

RFM Score: X42, X41

Who They Are:

Customers who return often, but do not spend a lot.

Marketing Strategies:

Focus on increasing monetization through product recommendations based on past purchases and incentives tied to spending thresholds.

For example:

This company pairs financial discounts with spending thresholds to drive repeat purchaes and increase customer profitability.

Newest Customers¶

RFM Score: 41X

Who They Are:

First time buyers on your site.

Marketing Strategies:

Having clear strategies in place for first time buyers such as triggered welcome emails.

For example:

Starbucks use email to bring customers into their loyalty rewards program.

Lost Valued Customer (At Risk Customers)¶

RFM Score: 144, 133

Who They Are:

customers who purchased often and spent big amounts, but haven’t purchased recently.

Marketing Strategies:

Send them personalized reactivation campaigns to reconnect, and offer renewals and helpful products to encourage another purchase.

Can’t Lose Customers¶

RFM Score: 14x , 13x , 24x, 23x

Who They Are:

(About to churn Customers) customers who used to visit and purchase quite often, but haven’t been visiting recently.

Marketing Strategies:

Bring them back with relevant promotions, and run surveys to find out what went wrong and avoid losing them to a competitor.

Lost Cheap Customers¶

RFM Score: 111

Who They Are:

Last purchase long ago, purchased few and spend little.

Marketing Strategies:

Don't spend too much trying to re-acquire.

Segmentation of customers using K-means Clustering way¶

we will divide the customers based on RFM values three times differently¶

Two Segments, then Three Segments, and then Four Segments¶

After each segmenting, we are going to see:¶

Summary Statistics for each cluster,¶

Relative importance of cluster attributes compared to population,¶

and a snake plot to notice the differences of RFM values between segments with different number of clusters¶

checking for each one of the k-means assumptions¶

1 Symmetric distribution of each variable (Not Skewed)

2 Same Centering: all variabes have the same average values (so, each metric/variable has an equal weight in the k-means calculation)

3 Same Scaling: all variables have the same variance (scaling the variance of each variable to the same level)

solutions

  • Skewness problem is resolved by logarithmatic transformation to each of the skewed variables (works only with positve valus) different averages and variances should be centered and scaled

  • Applying a scaler from sklearn library to center and scale all three values

# Centering and scaling the average and the variance/standard deviation respectively at the same time.

#Initializing a scaler

#Fiting the scaler

#Scaling and centering the data

#checking the optimum number of clusters
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans

sse = {}

# Fit KMeans and calculate SSE for each k
for k in range(1, 16):
  
    # Initialize KMeans with k clusters
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    
    # Fit KMeans on the normalized dataset
    kmeans.fit(rfm_normal)
    
    # Assign sum of squared distances to k element of dictionary
    sse[k] = kmeans.inertia_
    
plt.title('The Elbow Method')
plt.xlabel('Number of k'); plt.ylabel('SSE')
sns.pointplot(x=list(sse.keys()), y=list(sse.values()))
plt.show();

TWO Segments by K-means¶

In [47]:
#divide the customers by only two segments based on RFM values using K-means algorithm

# Initialize KMeans
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=2, random_state=1) 

# Fit k-means clustering on the normalized data set
kmeans.fit(rfm_normal)

# Extract cluster labels
cluster_labels = kmeans.labels_


# Create a DataFrame by adding a new cluster label column
rfm_k2 = rfm_values.assign(Cluster=cluster_labels)


# Calculate average RFM values and segment sizes per each cluster
rfm_k2.groupby(['Cluster']).agg({
    'Recency': 'mean',
    'Frequency': 'mean',
    'Monetary': ['mean', 'count']
  }).round(2)

#Creating the relative importance table for each RFM values based on Two segments.

relative_imp_k2 = cluster_avg / population_avg -1

plt.title('Relative importance of RFM Attributes')

#Adding a column Cluster2 to assign a cluster label for each row of the normalized rfm_normal
rfm_normal['Cluster2'] = rfm_k2['Cluster']

#for easier plotting in snake plot, we melt the data into a long format, so RFM values and metric names are stored in 1 column each 
rfm_melt = pd.melt(rfm_normal.reset_index(),id_vars=['Customer ID','Cluster2'],
                        value_vars=['Recency','Frequency','Monetary'],var_name='Metric',value_name='Value')

#plotting the snake graph
plt.title('Snake plot of standardized variables')
sns.lineplot(x='Metric', y='Value', hue='Cluster2', data=rfm_melt)
plt.show();

It seems that clustering with different number of segments can give different insights. So, I think there's no right or wrong number of segments, but there's a better number of segments.¶

The best decision to make here is to consult the person with the domain business knowledge and let them see which number of segments is more suitable for the business needs.¶
